l societies on the Nile and the Niger with metropolitan power, the survival of independent Ethiopia, Bismarck's manipulation of imperial diplomacy for European ends, the race for imperial possession in the 1880s, and the rapid setting of the imperial sun. Combining a sensitivity to historical detail with a judicious search for general patterns, Empires will engage the attention of social scientists in many disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImperialism. 4aEngland. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Imperialism.2bisacsh  aColonialism & Post-Colonialism.  aEuropean imperialism.  aathenian empire .  abritish empire.  acolonialism.  acultural imperialism.  adifferent empires.  adiversity of empires.  aempires.  aexpansionism.  ahistorical sociology of empires.  ahistory of empires.  ahistory of politics .  aimperial motivation.  aimperialism and capitalism.  aimperialism and capitalsm .  aimperialism and empire.  aimperialism.  aintroduction to European imperialism.  alife cycle of empires .  ametropoles.  aottoman empire.  apatterns of imperialism.  aperipheries.  apolitical societies.  aroman empire .  asocial change.  asocial scientists .  aspanish empire.  aspartan hegemony .  atheories of imperialism.  atheory of politics.  aworld politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173413740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501734137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501734137/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKAL